Datasets

All datasets for the Exercises are either defined inline, provided within the core tidyverse packages (table1, table2, table4a, table4b), or provided in the fivethirtyeight package (drinks).

The Case Study dataset is stored in the data folder and called users_top7_2020.csv.

Exercises

Exercise 1

Recreate the plot below showing the change in cases over time using table2. What do you need to do first?

Solution

The data needs to be tidied up. The pivot_wider function will help accomplish that.

Code 
# first, need to tidy the data for the cases and population
table2_tidy <- table2 |> 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = "type", 
    values_from = "count")

Exercise 2

Tidy the simple tibble of M&M data below and drop the NA values.

Do you need to make it wider or longer? What are the variables in your tidy version? What argument drops the NA values?

Code 
# simple tibble of M&M data
mm_data <- tribble(
  ~mm_type, ~blue, ~orange, ~green, ~yellow, ~brown, ~red, ~cyan_blue,
  "plain",  6,     18,      12,     6,       7,      7,    NA,
  "peanut", NA,    11,      9,      1,       12,       8,    15
)
Solution

This data frame needs to be made longer. The variables in the tidy version is color. The observations are the untidy column heads âblueâ, âorangeâ, âgreenâ, etc. The use of na.omit() will remove NA values for the peanut m and m blue count and the plain m and m cyan blue count.

Code 
  mm_data |> 
    pivot_longer(
        cols = c("blue", "orange", "green", "yellow", "brown", "red", "cyan_blue"),
        names_to = "color",
        values_to = "count"
    ) |>
  na.omit()

Exercise 5

What happens if you use pivot_wider() on this table so that we have a dataset with 3 columns (respondent_name, age, height) and why?

Fix the issue by adding a new column.

Code 
# dataset/table
people <- tribble(
  ~respondent_name,  ~key,    ~value,
  #-----------------|--------|------
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       45,
  "Phillip Woods",   "height",   186,
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       50,
  "Jessica Cordero", "age",       37,
  "Jessica Cordero", "height",   156
)
Solution

If trying to use pivot_wider, this results in observation for age potentially being a list because Phillip Woods has multiple values listed for âageâ.

Code 
## updated data
people_updated <- tribble(
  ~respondent_name,  ~key,    ~value, ~time,
  #-----------------|--------|-------|------
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       45,  "t1",
  "Phillip Woods",   "height",   186,  "t1",
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       50,  "t2",
  "Jessica Cordero", "age",       37,  "t1",
  "Jessica Cordero", "height",   156,  "t1"
)


people_updated |>
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = key,
    values_from = value,
    )
# A tibble: 3 Ã 4

1 Phillip Woods   t1       45    186
2 Phillip Woods   t2       50     NA
3 Jessica Cordero t1       37    156

Case Study

Tinder is interested in knowing more about their most active users, specifically their 7 most active users during 2020. They want to visualize the matches, likes, and passes over time for each user.

Solution

From these graphs, we can conclude that typically the number of matches and likes tend to remain at similar levels throughout the year (with a few exceptions). In most instances, the number of likes were slightly higher than the number of matches, which makes sense because most people will not receive likes back 100% of the time. For the most part, the number of likes and matches stay consistent throughout the year, with the exception of one user (user id 4afedf50a0e49727cc88dd23362c0074, seen in the top and right most graph) who sees a spike in likes in April. There are brief periods where the number of passes tend to spike among these users. During April, we see a spike in the number of passes for three out of the seven top users. The reason behind this is unclear, perhaps indicating underlying seasonal changes in dating preferences (perhaps these usersâ swiping criteria raised or change coming out of the winter, making them more likely to pass instead of like/match). One users also saw an increased number of passes as the year went on (user id cef50ce50692bb1260ae383c8e2a029c, seen in the lower and right most graph) but returning to a lower pass rate in December. These trends indicate that there is no consistent pattern dictating swiping activity throughout the year across all Top 7 Tinder Users in 2020. A few broader take aways can be made: number of likes tend to be larger than the number of matches and matching activity is generally stable throughout the year with no major spikes among these users. Additional study should go into why there are spikes in pass activity (and occasionally liking activity) throughout the year, maybe expanding the search to top 10% of all Tinder users from 2020.
